<h3>Detailed Description</h3>
<h4>Aims</h4>
<p></p>
<br><br>

<h4>Plans and Progress</h4>
<p></p>
<br><br>

<h4>Roles</h4>
<p></p>
<br><br>

<h4>Scope and Limits</h4>
<p>The scope of this project involves the ability to interlink communication of tasks towards multiple internet connectable household appliances, smart devices, and be able organize them and operate them all from the convenience of an application on your internet capable mobile device. This is the major priority of Telkom+ and our focus, while we are focusing on that primarily. Our secondary opportunity to provide additional benefits compared to our competitors is the implementation of an application controlled power strip that allows control of which devices are connected and be able to turn them on or off allowing for a remote on/off switch on applications that can be used to save power, and turn on a certain device the same time another is being utilized. While this is another deliverable that Telkom+ aims to achieve, this is not our main priority as we believe that the successful implantation of the main application to be developed is the main selling point to our idea.</p>
<br><br>

<h4>Tools and Technologies</h4>
<p>Our base software used to create this is Raspberry Pi, we would need this to create the device that connects the “non-smart” devices together. We would also need the licences for current programming software’s for Android such as, Java, Kotlin, C# or C++ just to name a few and software’s for Apple like, Swift. We would need hardware to create the adaptor for “non-smart” devices and the Raspberry Pi. Our group has experience programming in Java, C and some Micro bit experience, but the skills in these categories are still basic. None of us have any experience with Swift, Kotlin or Raspberry Pi, and this project gives us a chance to learn and pick up a few things for these languages and hardware.</p>
<br><br>

<h4>Testing</h4>
<p></p>
<br><br>

<h4>Timeframe</h4>
<p></p>
<br><br>

<h4>Risks</h4>
<p>A major risk about creating a new product and application is that it might not take off, all the funding and time spent might all be wasted if the product doesn’t have consumers. Some of the language to code for the application may be learnt slower than others and this might slow down the progress of developing the application and the functions. The documentation between the group might be hard to understand or might not even exist, this can affect the progress of the development too. Another risk could be the ability to transfer documents, the uncertainty that someone might intercept the documents or that some members are unable to send through documents due to their internet restrictions. A major risk would consist of our adaptor being inadequate to grant access for “non-smart” devices to connect with the Wi-Fi making it a smart device. The Raspberry Pi or similar products might be difficult to understand or achieve our desired goal.</p>
